273
00:11:41,920 --> 00:11:44,920
So the dimensions of the space of states

274
00:11:44,920 --> 00:11:48,920
can be very, very much larger than the dimension...

275
00:11:48,920 --> 00:11:50,920
Take a particle moving in a room.

276
00:11:50,920 --> 00:11:52,920
There are three dimensions for it to move in,

277
00:11:52,920 --> 00:11:54,920
but there's a huge, huge number of possible states

278
00:11:54,920 --> 00:11:57,920
of the particle, orthogonal states.

279
00:11:57,920 --> 00:11:59,920
So they're not connected in any simple way.

280
00:11:59,920 --> 00:12:00,920
Okay.

281
00:12:00,920 --> 00:12:02,920
Now...

282
00:12:02,920 --> 00:12:04,920
Oh, I think I lost this.

283
00:12:04,920 --> 00:12:05,920
All right.

284
00:12:05,920 --> 00:12:09,920
So you can always find a mutually orthogonal set

285
00:12:09,920 --> 00:12:10,920
of unit vectors.

286
00:12:10,920 --> 00:12:12,920
They're called basis vectors.

287
00:12:12,920 --> 00:12:15,920
They're not unique, but once you find the basis,

288
00:12:15,920 --> 00:12:17,920
you have a basis.

289
00:12:17,920 --> 00:12:19,920
And so let's imagine then that

290
00:12:19,920 --> 00:12:21,920
we have a set of basis vectors.

291
00:12:21,920 --> 00:12:22,920
We'll call them n,

292
00:12:22,920 --> 00:12:26,420
where n is a numerical

293
00:12:26,420 --> 00:12:29,920
integer that can run from one...

294
00:12:29,920 --> 00:12:31,920
to the dimension of the space.

295
00:12:31,920 --> 00:12:34,920
We have d such vectors,

296
00:12:34,920 --> 00:12:39,920
and they're orthogonal to each other, mutually orthogonal.

297
00:12:39,920 --> 00:12:43,920
So that means that m and n give zero,

298
00:12:43,920 --> 00:12:45,920
unless m is equal to n,

299
00:12:45,920 --> 00:12:47,920
in which case it gives one.

300
00:12:47,920 --> 00:12:51,920
So the symbol for that is the Kronecker delta symbol,

301
00:12:51,920 --> 00:12:53,920
and the Kronecker delta symbol simply means

302
00:12:53,920 --> 00:12:55,920
the right-hand side is one

303
00:12:55,920 --> 00:12:57,920
if m is equal to n,

304
00:12:57,920 --> 00:12:59,920
and zero if m is not equal to n.

305
00:12:59,920 --> 00:13:00,920
All right.

306
00:13:00,920 --> 00:13:04,920
So that's basically the definition of a basis set,

307
00:13:04,920 --> 00:13:06,920
or a set of basis vectors,

308
00:13:06,920 --> 00:13:07,920
for a...

309
00:13:07,920 --> 00:13:08,920
uh...

310
00:13:08,920 --> 00:13:12,920
for a space of the kind we're talking about.

311
00:13:12,920 --> 00:13:15,920
Now, um...

312
00:13:15,920 --> 00:13:17,920
here's an interesting theorem,

313
00:13:17,920 --> 00:13:19,920
which is hardly a theorem.

314
00:13:19,920 --> 00:13:21,920
It's more or less obvious,

315
00:13:21,920 --> 00:13:25,920
that if you have a basis set...

316
00:13:25,920 --> 00:13:27,420
if you have a basis

317
00:13:27,420 --> 00:13:28,920
set which has as many vectors

318
00:13:28,920 --> 00:13:31,920
as there are dimensions in the space,

319
00:13:31,920 --> 00:13:34,920
then it follows that any vector whatever

320
00:13:34,920 --> 00:13:36,920
can be expanded

321
00:13:36,920 --> 00:13:38,920
as a set of...

322
00:13:38,920 --> 00:13:40,920
sum of the basis vectors

323
00:13:40,920 --> 00:13:41,920
with coefficients,

324
00:13:41,920 --> 00:13:42,920
with a set of coefficients.

325
00:13:42,920 --> 00:13:45,920
Let's call those coefficients a sub n

326
00:13:45,920 --> 00:13:46,920
times n,

327
00:13:46,920 --> 00:13:48,920
summed on n.

328
00:13:48,920 --> 00:13:51,920
In other words, this is just saying that any vector

329
00:13:51,920 --> 00:13:53,920
anywhere can be expanded in terms of,

330
00:13:53,920 --> 00:13:54,920
uh...

331
00:13:54,920 --> 00:13:55,920
in three dimensions,

332
00:13:55,920 --> 00:13:56,920
the three basis vectors,

333
00:13:56,920 --> 00:13:57,920
or whatever.

334
00:13:57,920 --> 00:13:58,920
All right.

335
00:13:58,920 --> 00:13:59,920
And now,

336
00:13:59,920 --> 00:14:03,920
we can relate the, um...

337
00:14:03,920 --> 00:14:06,920
the expansion coefficients here

338
00:14:06,920 --> 00:14:07,920
to the inner products of these sum of them.

339
00:14:07,920 --> 00:14:09,920
So, let's take the inner products of these

340
00:14:09,920 --> 00:14:10,920
with the basis vectors.

341
00:14:10,920 --> 00:14:11,920
Let's do that.

342
00:14:11,920 --> 00:14:13,920
Just take the inner product of this

343
00:14:13,920 --> 00:14:15,920
equation with any vector,

344
00:14:15,920 --> 00:14:16,920
uh... on the left,

345
00:14:16,920 --> 00:14:19,920
with any one of the basis vectors on the left.

346
00:14:19,920 --> 00:14:22,920
And so we find that m psi

347
00:14:22,920 --> 00:14:24,920
is equal to sum on n,

348
00:14:24,920 --> 00:14:26,920
a sub n,

349
00:14:26,920 --> 00:14:28,920
m n.

350
00:14:28,920 --> 00:14:30,920
Now, this is a sum on n,

351
00:14:30,920 --> 00:14:32,920
but there's only one term,

352
00:14:32,920 --> 00:14:34,920
because only when n is equal to m

353
00:14:34,920 --> 00:14:35,920
do we get an answer,

354
00:14:35,920 --> 00:14:36,920
do we get something non-zero.

355
00:14:36,920 --> 00:14:37,920
When n is not equal to m,

356
00:14:37,920 --> 00:14:38,920
they're orthogonal.

357
00:14:38,920 --> 00:14:40,920
When n is equal to m,

358
00:14:40,920 --> 00:14:41,920
uh...

359
00:14:41,920 --> 00:14:42,920
then you get the answer number one,

360
00:14:42,920 --> 00:14:43,920
just one.

361
00:14:43,920 --> 00:14:46,920
And so you get only one term in here,

362
00:14:46,920 --> 00:14:49,920
and that term is just equal to a m.

363
00:14:49,920 --> 00:14:50,920
All right.

364
00:14:50,920 --> 00:14:51,920
It's summed on n,

365
00:14:51,920 --> 00:14:52,920
but we sort of picked out,

366
00:14:52,920 --> 00:14:54,920
we've selected out m

367
00:14:54,920 --> 00:14:56,920
to project onto psi,

368
00:14:56,920 --> 00:15:00,920
and the whole answer then is just a m.

369
00:15:00,920 --> 00:15:01,920
All right.

370
00:15:01,920 --> 00:15:03,920
So that's a nice, simple fact

371
00:15:03,920 --> 00:15:05,920
that the expansion coefficients here,

372
00:15:05,920 --> 00:15:07,920
for a given vector,

373
00:15:07,920 --> 00:15:10,920
are nothing but the inner products

374
00:15:10,920 --> 00:15:13,920
of the psi vector

375
00:15:13,920 --> 00:15:15,920
with the basis vectors.

376
00:15:15,920 --> 00:15:17,920
That tells us what the a's are.

377
00:15:17,920 --> 00:15:19,920
If we take the, uh...

378
00:15:19,920 --> 00:15:20,920
Now I can rewrite the equation.

379
00:15:20,920 --> 00:15:22,920
Let's rewrite this equation.

380
00:15:22,920 --> 00:15:24,920
We now know what the a's are.

381
00:15:24,920 --> 00:15:26,920
Let's write it in the following form.

382
00:15:26,920 --> 00:15:30,920
Psi is equal to sum on n,

383
00:15:30,920 --> 00:15:32,920
and now instead of writing a,

384
00:15:32,920 --> 00:15:34,920
I'm going to write this inner product.

385
00:15:35,920 --> 00:15:42,920
The inner product is just n psi.

386
00:15:42,920 --> 00:15:46,920
That's a n times n.

387
00:15:46,920 --> 00:15:49,920
I've taken the liberty of writing the coefficient

388
00:15:49,920 --> 00:15:51,920
on the right side of the vector

389
00:15:51,920 --> 00:15:53,920
instead of the left side of the vector.

390
00:15:53,920 --> 00:15:55,920
That doesn't, uh...

391
00:15:55,920 --> 00:15:59,920
You are allowed to write 3 times psi

392
00:15:59,920 --> 00:16:01,920
as equal to psi times 3.

393
00:16:01,920 --> 00:16:03,920
That doesn't, uh...

394
00:16:03,920 --> 00:16:05,920
No objection to that.

395
00:16:05,920 --> 00:16:07,920
So this is a number.

396
00:16:07,920 --> 00:16:09,920
This is the inner product.

397
00:16:09,920 --> 00:16:11,920
This is the nth basis vector.

398
00:16:11,920 --> 00:16:13,920
It's the same formula,

399
00:16:13,920 --> 00:16:15,920
except that I've used for the coefficient here, a,

400
00:16:15,920 --> 00:16:17,920
the inner product.

401
00:16:17,920 --> 00:16:20,920
Now I have an interesting equation.

402
00:16:20,920 --> 00:16:23,920
I'm going to read this the following way.

403
00:16:23,920 --> 00:16:25,920
I'm going to read this,

404
00:16:25,920 --> 00:16:27,920
I'm going to separate it in the following way.

405
00:16:27,920 --> 00:16:29,920
I'm going to invent a new symbol.

406
00:16:29,920 --> 00:16:31,920
The new symbol is the sum

407
00:16:31,920 --> 00:16:33,920
of n times n.

408
00:16:33,920 --> 00:16:35,920
What on earth does that mean?

409
00:16:35,920 --> 00:16:39,920
We've never defined putting vectors back to back like that.

410
00:16:39,920 --> 00:16:41,420
But now I'll tell you

411
00:16:41,420 --> 00:16:42,920
exactly what such an object is.

412
00:16:42,920 --> 00:16:45,920
When you put vectors back to back like that,

413
00:16:45,920 --> 00:16:48,920
any two vectors, it doesn't have to be basis vectors,

414
00:16:48,920 --> 00:16:50,920
take any two vectors,

415
00:16:50,920 --> 00:16:52,920
let's call it a and b,

416
00:16:52,920 --> 00:16:54,920
put them back to back,

417
00:16:54,920 --> 00:16:56,920
what you get is a linear operator.

418
00:16:56,920 --> 00:16:58,920
You get an operator,

419
00:16:58,920 --> 00:17:00,920
and the way that it operates

420
00:17:00,920 --> 00:17:03,920
is when it multiplies a vector,

421
00:17:03,920 --> 00:17:06,920
you just take the inner product

422
00:17:06,920 --> 00:17:08,920
of b with psi,

423
00:17:08,920 --> 00:17:10,920
and multiply it by a.

424
00:17:10,920 --> 00:17:12,920
So this is an object

425
00:17:12,920 --> 00:17:14,920
which when you

426
00:17:14,920 --> 00:17:16,920
apply it to a vector,

427
00:17:16,920 --> 00:17:18,920
with the rule

428
00:17:18,920 --> 00:17:20,420
that you just take the

429
00:17:20,420 --> 00:17:21,920
inner product of b with psi,

430
00:17:21,920 --> 00:17:23,920
what you get back is another vector.

431
00:17:23,920 --> 00:17:25,920
It's a linear operator.

432
00:17:25,920 --> 00:17:27,920
It's called a dyad,

433
00:17:27,920 --> 00:17:29,920
a pair of vectors back to back like that.

434
00:17:29,920 --> 00:17:32,920
All dyads like that are linear operators.

435
00:17:32,920 --> 00:17:36,920
And we can now read off from this equation

436
00:17:36,920 --> 00:17:39,920
what this operator is.

437
00:17:39,920 --> 00:17:42,920
It's an operator which does nothing.

438
00:17:42,920 --> 00:17:45,920
When, let's move this over a little bit.

439
00:17:45,920 --> 00:17:49,920
Let's put psi over, well,

440
00:17:49,920 --> 00:17:51,920
let's think of this as an operator

441
00:17:51,920 --> 00:17:53,920
which hits psi.

442
00:17:53,920 --> 00:17:56,920
I've got an extra redundant vertical sign here,

443
00:17:56,920 --> 00:17:58,920
but that's alright.

444
00:17:58,920 --> 00:18:00,920
What does it do?

445
00:18:00,920 --> 00:18:02,920
When this construction hits psi,

446
00:18:02,920 --> 00:18:04,920
it just gives psi back.

447
00:18:04,920 --> 00:18:06,920
So this tells you immediately

448
00:18:06,920 --> 00:18:09,920
what the meaning of this object is.

449
00:18:09,920 --> 00:18:11,920
It's just a unit operator.

450
00:18:13,920 --> 00:18:15,920
How do you read it?

451
00:18:15,920 --> 00:18:17,920
When this object over here

452
00:18:17,920 --> 00:18:19,920
hits any vector at all,

453
00:18:19,920 --> 00:18:22,920
it gives back the same vector.

454
00:18:22,920 --> 00:18:27,920
And that's called,

455
00:18:27,920 --> 00:18:30,920
what it's called is the resolution of the identity,

456
00:18:30,920 --> 00:18:32,920
but any time you see this symbol,

457
00:18:32,920 --> 00:18:34,920
sum over the vectors of

458
00:18:34,920 --> 00:18:36,920
n's back to back like that,

459
00:18:36,920 --> 00:18:39,920
it is just the unit operator.

460
00:18:39,920 --> 00:18:41,920
But in that case,

461
00:18:41,920 --> 00:18:44,920
n can't be just any vector.

462
00:18:44,920 --> 00:18:46,920
n, n is summed over.

463
00:18:46,920 --> 00:18:48,920
n is a sum over a basis.

464
00:18:48,920 --> 00:18:50,920
It has to be a basis.

465
00:18:50,920 --> 00:18:52,920
Yes, it has to be a basis.

466
00:18:52,920 --> 00:18:54,920
It has to be a set of orthogonal,

467
00:18:54,920 --> 00:18:56,920
we use that here,

468
00:18:56,920 --> 00:18:58,920
when we calculated that

469
00:18:58,920 --> 00:19:01,920
the coefficients were equal to psi times m,

470
00:19:01,920 --> 00:19:04,920
we used the orthogonality

471
00:19:04,920 --> 00:19:07,920
and the unit character of each one of these vectors.

472
00:19:07,920 --> 00:19:09,920
So yes, we did use that.

473
00:19:09,920 --> 00:19:11,920
These must be a basis.

474
00:19:11,920 --> 00:19:14,920
Excuse me.

475
00:19:14,920 --> 00:19:17,920
Can you call that the eigen...

476
00:19:17,920 --> 00:19:20,920
This is just the resolution of the identity.

477
00:19:20,920 --> 00:19:21,920
That's the word for it.

478
00:19:21,920 --> 00:19:22,920
Yeah, I understand.

479
00:19:22,920 --> 00:19:23,920
But if I look at it,

480
00:19:23,920 --> 00:19:24,920
it looks to me like

481
00:19:24,920 --> 00:19:25,920
it's with an eigenvalue of one.

482
00:19:25,920 --> 00:19:26,920
Yes.

483
00:19:26,920 --> 00:19:27,920
And the eigen...

484
00:19:27,920 --> 00:19:28,920
Yes.

485
00:19:28,920 --> 00:19:29,920
The unit operator,

486
00:19:29,920 --> 00:19:31,920
every vector is an eigenvector.

487
00:19:31,920 --> 00:19:33,920
Every vector is an eigenvector of the unit operator

488
00:19:33,920 --> 00:19:34,920
with eigenvalue one.

489
00:19:34,920 --> 00:19:37,920
The unit operator is a special operator

490
00:19:37,920 --> 00:19:39,920
that has all its...

491
00:19:39,920 --> 00:19:41,920
Every vector is an eigenvector of it,

492
00:19:41,920 --> 00:19:44,920
and every vector has eigenvalue plus one.

493
00:19:44,920 --> 00:19:46,920
So it's...

494
00:19:46,920 --> 00:19:48,920
And it just says that one on any vector

495
00:19:48,920 --> 00:19:50,920
gives you back the same vector.

496
00:19:50,920 --> 00:19:51,920
Why?

497
00:19:51,920 --> 00:19:52,920
I is the identity.

498
00:19:52,920 --> 00:19:54,920
It's called the identity.

499
00:19:54,920 --> 00:19:55,920
Good.

500
00:19:55,920 --> 00:19:57,920
All right, but now,

501
00:19:57,920 --> 00:19:59,920
we might be interested in a subspace.

502
00:19:59,920 --> 00:20:01,920
Let's define...

503
00:20:01,920 --> 00:20:02,920
some subspaces,

504
00:20:02,920 --> 00:20:03,920
some interesting subspaces.

505
00:20:03,920 --> 00:20:07,920
Subspaces correspond to certain observable questions

506
00:20:07,920 --> 00:20:16,920
that you could ask or that you might answer.

507
00:20:16,920 --> 00:20:17,920
So, for example,

508
00:20:17,920 --> 00:20:19,920
let's suppose that we have some operator,

509
00:20:19,920 --> 00:20:21,920
some observable,

510
00:20:21,920 --> 00:20:23,920
some Hermitian operator

511
00:20:23,920 --> 00:20:25,920
that I'll call k.

512
00:20:25,920 --> 00:20:27,920
It's something that we can measure.

513
00:20:27,920 --> 00:20:28,920
It has an eigenvalue spectrum.

514
00:20:28,920 --> 00:20:29,920
It's Hermitian.

515
00:20:29,920 --> 00:20:30,920
It has all the properties

516
00:20:30,920 --> 00:20:33,920
that we identify with an observable quantity.

517
00:20:33,920 --> 00:20:35,920
And let's suppose that we have

518
00:20:35,920 --> 00:20:38,920
a eigenvector A of it

519
00:20:38,920 --> 00:20:41,920
with eigenvalue lambda.

520
00:20:41,920 --> 00:20:46,920
That just says that if you measure k

521
00:20:46,920 --> 00:20:48,920
when the system is in the state A,

522
00:20:48,920 --> 00:20:50,920
you will get the answer lambda for certain.

523
00:20:50,920 --> 00:20:53,920
Let's suppose there's another eigenvector

524
00:20:53,920 --> 00:20:55,920
with exactly the same eigenvalue,

525
00:20:55,920 --> 00:20:57,920
not a different eigenvalue,

526
00:20:57,920 --> 00:20:58,920
the same one.

527
00:20:58,920 --> 00:20:59,920
Different vector,

528
00:20:59,920 --> 00:21:03,920
in fact, linearly independent of A,

529
00:21:03,920 --> 00:21:05,920
so it's not pointing in the same direction as A.

530
00:21:05,920 --> 00:21:07,920
It's not a multiple of A

531
00:21:07,920 --> 00:21:10,920
with exactly the same eigenvalue.

532
00:21:10,920 --> 00:21:15,920
Then, any linear combination of A and B,

533
00:21:15,920 --> 00:21:20,920
let's call it alpha A plus beta B,

534
00:21:20,920 --> 00:21:22,920
any combination like that

535
00:21:22,920 --> 00:21:24,920
is also an eigenvector of k

536
00:21:24,920 --> 00:21:26,920
with exactly the same eigenvalue.

537
00:21:26,920 --> 00:21:28,920
It's easy to check.

538
00:21:28,920 --> 00:21:30,920
You just apply k to this,

539
00:21:30,920 --> 00:21:33,920
but each term just gets multiplied by lambda,

540
00:21:33,920 --> 00:21:36,920
so the lambda comes on the outside.

541
00:21:36,920 --> 00:21:39,920
If we apply k to it,

542
00:21:39,920 --> 00:21:41,920
the k just goes right through

543
00:21:41,920 --> 00:21:43,920
and multiplies each one of these by lambda.

544
00:21:43,920 --> 00:21:46,920
The whole thing is just a multiplication by lambda.

545
00:21:46,920 --> 00:21:49,920
And so any linear combination

546
00:21:49,920 --> 00:21:52,920
of a pair of eigenvectors with the same eigenvalue

547
00:21:52,920 --> 00:21:56,920
is also an eigenvector with that eigenvalue.

548
00:21:56,920 --> 00:21:57,920
In other words,

549
00:21:57,920 --> 00:21:59,920
what we're beginning to discover

550
00:21:59,920 --> 00:22:02,920
is that there's a subspace.

551
00:22:02,920 --> 00:22:03,920
A subspace,

552
00:22:03,920 --> 00:22:05,920
ah, what does a subspace mean?

553
00:22:05,920 --> 00:22:09,920
A subspace means a set of vectors

554
00:22:09,920 --> 00:22:11,920
which are closed under addition

555
00:22:11,920 --> 00:22:13,920
and which have the property

556
00:22:13,920 --> 00:22:15,920
that they themselves are a vector space

557
00:22:15,920 --> 00:22:18,920
but might be lower dimensional.

